[2] Uganda (Cholera & Dysentery)
Date: Mon 17 Feb 2003
From: Malimbo Mugagga <malimbom@hotmail.com>
Source: Uganda Weekly Epidemiological Newsletters [edited]

5th Week of 2003 (Week ending 2 Feb 2003)
Cholera has persisted in the 4 districts of Bundibugyo, Kasese, Hoima, and
Nebbi. The district of Kampala also reported more cholera, but all of them
originating from Wakiso district. Ministry of Health is working with the
affected districts to control the situation.
Dysentery was registered by 51 (96 percent) of the districts that reported.
Though it decreased in some districts, it increased in others. Whereas Apac
district registered a marked upsurge of dysentery from 28 cases last week
to 128 cases this week, Kalangala district reported a drastic decrease from
113 last week to 13 this week. Other districts that have continued to
report high numbers of dysentery cases are Arua (81 cases), Moyo (59),
Kotido (51 cases), and Yumbe (50 cases). Districts need to step up
community health education on proper hygiene practices as a control measure
to dysentery.
3rd Week of 2003 (Week ending 19 Jan 2003)
Cholera cases were reported in 6 districts this week. There was a general
decrease in the number of reported cases. Kasese reported a reduction from
42 cases last week to 29 cases this week, while in Kampala cases have
further dropped from 13 to 7 cases this week. Other districts with cholera
cases were Arua (7 cases this week compared to 12 last week), Bundibugyo (7
cases from 11 last week), and Masindi (1 case compared to 2 last week).
However Nebbi district reported 6 cases when there had been none in the
previous week. The Ministry of Health is working with the affected
districts to control the situation.
Dysentery cases remained high in the northern region. The leading districts
in dysentery cases reporting are Kotido (156 cases), Gulu (121), and Arua
(52 cases with 1 deaths). Dysentery cases were reported 49 other districts.
2nd Week of 2003 (Week ending 12 Jan 2003)
Cholera cases were reported in 6 districts this week. There was a further
rise in cases reported by Kasese from 37 last week to 42 this week, while
in Kampala cases dropped from 19 to 13 this week. Other districts with
cholera cases were Arua (12 cases this week compared to 11 last week),
Bundibugyo (11 cases from 8 last week), Masindi (2 cases with 1 death, no
cases last week), and Mayuge (1 case this week, 4 cases last week).
Ministry of Health is working with the affected districts to control the
situation.
Dysentery cases were reported in all the 56 districts that submitted
reports. The outbreak in Kalangala intensified with cases rising from 24
last week to 113 this week. Other districts that have continued to report
high numbers of dysentery cases are Arua (96 cases), Pader (66), Moroto
(56), Kisoro (52), Moyo (49), and Bundibugyo (42). Poor sanitation and
personal hygiene practices are the risk factor for the reported upsurges in
dysentery cases.
2nd Week of 2003 (Week ending 5 Jan 2003
Cholera cases were reported in 6 districts this week. There was a further
rise in cases reported by Kasese from 37 last week to 42 this week, while
in Kampala cases dropped from 19 to 13 this week. Other districts with
cholera cases were Arua (12 cases this week compared to 11 last week),
Bundibugyo (11 cases from 8 last week), Masindi (2 cases with 1 death, no
cases last week) and Mayuge (1 case this week, 4 cases last week). Ministry
of Health is working with the affected districts to control the situation.
Dysentery cases were reported in all the 55 districts that submitted
reports. The outbreak in Kalangala intensified with cases rising to 113
this week. Other districts that have continued to report high numbers of
dysentery cases are Arua (96 cases), Pader (66), Moroto (56), Kisoro (52),
Moyo (49), and Bundibugyo (42). Poor sanitation and personal hygiene
practices are the risk factors [implicated in] the reported upsurges in
dysentery cases.
