[6] Mozambique
Date: 28 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency 27 Jan 2003 [edited]

Cholera hits parts of Mozambique
---------------------------
About 336 cases of cholera have been diagnosed and 10 people died of the
disease in Mozambique's central province of Sofala since it broke out in
December 2002, local media reported.
In Pemba, capital of the country's northern province of Cabo Delgado, the
local health authorities have reported 26 patients with symptoms of
diarrhea and vomiting. In Tete, another province in northern Mozambique,
there have been 20 cases of diarrhea.
Official sources were quoted as saying the Mozambican government and local
authorities are taking measures to check the spread of cholera in the
country. The government has urged the public to seriously observe health
precautions against the disease, the report said.
******
[7] India
Date: Mon, 3 Feb 2003 13:12:47 -0000
From: A-Lan Banks <a-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: Indian Express [edited]
<http://www.indianexpress.com/full_story.php?content_id=17750>

Cholera scare hit the residents of a hostel at the IIT [Indian Insitute of
Technology - Mod.LL], Chennai, when students fell ill due to suspected
contamination of drinking water.
On Sat 1 Feb 2003, more than 15 students who had been complaining of
dysentery and nausea since the previous evening were referred to the
hospital on the campus. Of them, 3, who developed complications, were
rushed to the Corporation-run Institute for Communicable Diseases, Tondiarpet.
According to ICD sources, the medical laboratory test report of one of the
IIT students confirmed cholera, while the reports of the other 2 patients
are awaited.
A few residents said the problem started on Fri, 31 Jan 2003 after they
consumed regular supply water as the water treatment plant at the institute
was under repair. A professor said apparently the private caterers in
charge of the hostel mess had ignored the cautionary note on serving boiled
water whenever the treatment plant stopped functioning.
More than 300 irate students refused to take lunch at the mess. However,
the Dean (students) Gokhale intervened and pacified them. The catering
staff have reportedly been told to wash all utensils with hot water for the
next few days and students are now being supplied purified bottled water.
The arrangement would continue till the leakage in the treatment plant is
rectified. The Dean said all students are out of danger now and that a
local monitoring committee would be set up with student representatives.
